references: The performance of the proposed framework is carried out by comparing the basic neural network architectures (i.e., multi-layer perception classifier (MLP) and CNN with a benchmark GNN architecture (i.e., GCN which consists of two graph convolution layers and a fully connected layer) - see Fig. 3(a) with performance metrics, i.e., MAE, as seen in the Eq. 9 and MedAE, to account for potential outliers in the loss values. It can be observed from Table I that the MAE and MedAE score of GCN is lower with around 52.7%percent52.752.7\% and 58.7%percent58.758.7\% less than MLP, and 38.9%percent38.938.9\% and 41.7%percent41.741.7\% lower than CNN respectively. The reason for these results is the use of the graph convolution layer is designed to handle sparse and long-range communication through the implementation of a message-passing algorithm.
